I often think that Millennials may be the last generation capable of genuinely appreciating art and forming connections with artists. They don't have that pressure to view everything through a critical, tinted lens.
We grew up in the golden age of media, when people shared a common understanding of pop culture, whereas today, this collective awareness has disappeared.
At that time, we could immerse ourselves directly without considering the source of the content, because in that era, tracing back to the origins was not easy.
We revered these artists as if they were deities, and there was no reason to question this worship. Thus, we established a "pseudo-social relationship" with them and regarded it as an indispensable part of our lives.
This also explains why we are so obsessed with nostalgia.
When The Office was still on air, my friends and I would gather every Thursday to watch the show together while eating pizza.
This is entirely different from our current experience of watching shows through streaming platforms. Streaming platforms usually release all 12 episodes at once, and everyone watches at their own pace. When posting about the plot on social media, they often add "spoiler warning," or simply discuss in specific groups.
Subconsciously, we all long to relive that sense of collective belonging that connected everyone together.
It's precisely because of our nostalgia that we keep rewatching TV shows like The Office or movies like The King of Queens, whose iconic lines, like memes, spread widely online.
We quote these iconic lines from the works and assume that most people can understand them.
Nowadays, even if something goes viral online, we cannot assume that everyone has seen it.
Now with information overload, there's just too much to pay attention to, and we can't really narrow it down... Do we still have a chance to escape from this state of information overload?
We keep discovering new media and new artists time and again, only to find that they are either predatory sexual offenders or stubborn individuals filled with prejudice, and this cycle is endlessly repetitive and exhausting.
We are caught between our nostalgia and the realization that the people who created the art we love may have serious moral flaws, and this conflicting mindset leaves us feeling lost.
We will be more cautious in forming "parasocial relationships" with artists.
We gradually realize that it is difficult to ensure one will not harm or exploit others if one wishes to gain wealth and power.
Due to the disappearance of collective media consciousness, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us maintain critical thinking.
Of course, some people are still stubbornly clinging to the idea of elevating others to a divine status, only to pretend to be shocked when their idols fall.
We are in an era of transformation, and I urgently want to know where we are heading.
Inclusion and safety should be the default.
